 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import transportation_tutorials as tt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "toc-hr-collapsed": false
   },
   "source": [
    "# Manipulating Geographic Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A [shapefile](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shapefile) is a data format that is actually a set of files\n",
    "containing geospatial information.  All of the related files have the same filename (except for the file\n",
    "extension) and must reside in the same directory.  Generally, there will be files with the ``shp`` extension \n",
    "containing geographic data, the ``dbf`` extension containing tabular data, and a few others.  The files\n",
    "can be read into python as a group and manipulated using the [GeoPandas](http://geopandas.org) package."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import geopandas as gpd"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Loading a Shapefile"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's load the SERPM8 TAZ shapefile.  This shapefile (actually a set of files)\n",
    "is included in the data of the tuturials package and can be accessed as shown.\n",
    "Loading a shapefile into Python using geopandas is a simple task using the\n",
    "[read_file](http://geopandas.org/reference/geopandas.read_file.html) function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "shapefile_filename = tt.data('SERPM8-TAZSHAPE')\n",
    "taz = gpd.read_file(shapefile_filename)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This will load the shapefile into a \n",
    "[GeoDataFrame](http://geopandas.org/reference.html#geodataframe) object, \n",
    "which is similar to\n",
    "a pandas DataFrame, but with a special *geometry* column that contains, \n",
    "as you might guess, geometric shape data contained in the *shp* part of \n",
    "the shapefile.  It also includes all the other\n",
    "various tabular data contained in the *dbf* part of the shapefile.  We\n",
    "can inspect the first few lines of the GeoDataFrame to see the contents,\n",
    "just like a regular DataFrame:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

    "Because this is the TAZ shapefile, we expect that the geometry column includes a set of \n",
    "[Polygon](https://shapely.readthedocs.io/en/stable/manual.html#polygons) values, as we\n",
    "can observe in the first few rows.  We can also easily check how many zones are included\n",
    "in the file by checking the length of the GeoDataFrame."
   ]
  },

    "Displaying the shapefile in a jupyter notebook can be accomplished by calling the \n",

    "method of the GeoDataFrame."
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Coordinate Reference Systems\n",
    "\n",
    "You might notice that the axis labels don't show latitude and longitude.\n",
    "That's because the TAZ file uses a \n",
    "different coordinate reference system (*crs*) for map projection.\n",
    "We can find what crs is being used by accessing the [crs](http://geopandas.org/projections.html#coordinate-reference-systems) attribute."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<Projected CRS: PROJCS[\"NAD83 / Florida East (ftUS)\",GEOGCS[\"NAD83 ...>\n",
       "Name: NAD83 / Florida East (ftUS)\n",
       "Axis Info [cartesian]:\n",
       "- [east]: Easting (US survey foot)\n",
       "- [north]: Northing (US survey foot)\n",
       "Area of Use:\n",
       "- undefined\n",
       "Coordinate Operation:\n",
       "- name: unnamed\n",
       "- method: Transverse Mercator\n",
       "Datum: North American Datum 1983\n",
       "- Ellipsoid: GRS 1980\n",
       "- Prime Meridian: Greenwich"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 7,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "taz.crs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Drop that code into [Google](http://www.google.com/search?q=epsg%3A2236)\n",
    "and you'll find that it's a special coordinate system for\n",
    "[mapping and engineering in eastern Florida](https://spatialreference.org/ref/epsg/nad83-florida-east-ftus/), which for this application may be perfectly reasonable.\n",
    "However, suppose we want to generate maps using plain old \n",
    "latitude and longitude. We can convert between CRS systems\n",
    "easily, like this:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "taz1 = taz.to_crs(epsg=4326)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = taz1.plot()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The map projection generated here is subtly different from the previous one.  If you look\n",
    "carefully, you'll note the shape of the second map is a bit wider than first.  This distortion\n",
    "is a natural part of the mapping projection, using plain latitude and longitude, as one\n",
    "degree of longitude is a different distance than one degree of latitude.  In Florida, the \n",
    "difference is relatively small, but it grows as you move north."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Selecting by Geography"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The SERPM8 region is quite large.  Let's suppose we only want to study a small\n",
    "portion of this region. Since we are working with Jupyter notebooks, we'll select \n",
    "an area to study around Jupiter, Florida. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Selection by Rectangular Envelope\n",
    "\n",
    "We can explicitly define some bounds for\n",
    "our study area:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "xmin = 905712.145924\n",
    "ymin = 905343.94408855\n",
    "xmax = 983346.68922847\n",
    "ymax = 981695.93140023"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then, to select only the TAZ's that are (at least partially) contained in the study area,\n",
    "we can use the ``cx`` indexer on GeoDataFrames.  This indexer works similarly to the ``loc``\n",
    "and ``iloc`` indexers on regular DataFrames, but selects not based on labels or tabular\n",
    "position, but instead selects based on geographic position."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "taz_jupiter = taz.cx[xmin:xmax, ymin:ymax]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The result of the selection is another GeoDataFrame, just as slicing\n",
    "using the ``loc``and ``iloc`` indexers on regular DataFrames creates\n",
    "a new DataFrame.  Thus, we can review how many TAZ's are in the selection \n",
    "in the same manner as we checked the number of TAZ's in the original shapefile."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "220"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 12,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "len(taz_jupiter)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And we can plot a map of the selected area, just as we did with \n",
    "the original data. Here, we'll draw the borders of the TAZ's in \n",
    "white for better contrast."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = taz_jupiter.plot(edgecolor='w')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Because Jupiter is in the northwest corner of the SERPM region, \n",
    "only the south and west boundaries of the study area are relevant\n",
    "in the selection definition.  Convenietly, just like other DataFrame\n",
    "indexers, the ``cx`` indexer allows for one-sided slices."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "True"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 14,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "taz_jupiter2 = taz.cx[xmin:, ymin:]\n",
    "taz_jupiter2.equals(taz_jupiter)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "One important note regarding the ``cx`` indexer is that it will \n",
    "select all features that are contained fully *or partially* in\n",
    "the selection area.  To illustrate, we can construct a GeoDataFrame\n",
    "consisting of the study area box, and draw it on a map of the \n",
    "selected zones."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from shapely.geometry import box\n",
    "from pyproj import CRS\n",
    "study_area = gpd.GeoDataFrame(geometry=[box(xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax)], crs=CRS.from_epsg(2236))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [
       "<div>\n",
       "<style scoped>\n",
       "    .dataframe tbody tr th:only-of-type {\n",
       "        vertical-align: middle;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "\n",
       "    .dataframe tbody tr th {\n",
       "        vertical-align: top;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "\n",
       "    .dataframe thead th {\n",
       "        text-align: right;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "</style>\n",
       "<table border=\"1\" class=\"dataframe\">\n",
       "  <thead>\n",
       "    <tr style=\"text-align: right;\">\n",
       "      <th></th>\n",
       "      <th>geometry</th>\n",
       "    </tr>\n",
       "  </thead>\n",
       "  <tbody>\n",
       "    <tr>\n",
       "      <th>0</th>\n",
       "      <td>POLYGON ((983346.689 905343.944, 983346.689 98...</td>\n",
       "    </tr>\n",
       "  </tbody>\n",
       "</table>\n",
       "</div>"
      ],
      "text/plain": [
       "                                            geometry\n",
       "0  POLYGON ((983346.689 905343.944, 983346.689 98..."
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 16,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "study_area"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = taz_jupiter.plot(edgecolor='w')\n",
    "transparent = (0,0,0,0)\n",
    "ax = study_area.plot(ax=ax, edgecolor='red', facecolor=transparent)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Selection by Polygon\n",
    "\n",
    "If the study area is not neatly defined by a rectangle but instead by some\n",
    "defined irregular polygon, it is still possible to filter the GeoDataFrame,\n",
    "but slightly more complicated.  We'll demonstrate by first constructing\n",
    "an irregular polygon."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from shapely.geometry import Polygon\n",
    "irregular_polygon = Polygon([\n",
    "    (973346, 935343),\n",
    "    (973346, 971695), \n",
    "    (912812, 973695), \n",
    "    (915812, 943695),  \n",
    "    (928812, 943695),  \n",
    "    (935712, 905343),  \n",
    "])\n",
    "ax = taz_jupiter.plot(edgecolor='w')\n",
    "lines = ax.plot(*irregular_polygon.exterior.xy, color='r')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To indentify those TAZ polygons that touch the polygon, we can use the \n",
    "``intersects`` method of GeoDataFrames."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

    "taz_jupiter"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This gives us a series that matches the GeoDataFrame, and identifies whether\n",
    "each row's geometry intersects the the polygon.  We can use that to filter\n",
    "the rows, to retain only those TAZ's of interest."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "taz_jupiter_irregular = taz_jupiter[taz_jupiter.intersects(irregular_polygon)]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "146"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 22,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "len(taz_jupiter_irregular)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This gives us a new GeoDataFrame that is potentially just a filtered view of the \n",
    "original, which can potentially lead to problems later ([see here](http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/indexing.html#indexing-view-versus-copy)).  To ensure we have a\n",
    "bonafide new GeoDataFrame, we can make sure it is a copy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "taz_jupiter_irregular = taz_jupiter_irregular.copy()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = taz_jupiter_irregular.plot(edgecolor='w')\n",
    "lines = ax.plot(*irregular_polygon.exterior.xy, color='r')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You may note, as with the rectangular selection, we still select any \n",
    "zone that has any part of the zone inside the polygon."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Clipping by Geography"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If instead we want to actually clip the geographic data at the study area frame,\n",
    "we can use the ``overlay`` function to get the intersection of the TAZ's and the\n",
    "study area."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "taz_jupiter_clip = gpd.overlay(taz, study_area.to_crs(taz.crs), how='intersection')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "By taking the intersection, we discard portions of the zone shapes that\n",
    "are outside the study area, as is illustrated when we map the results\n",
    "with the study area box."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = taz_jupiter_clip.plot(edgecolor='w')\n",
    "transparent = (0,0,0,0)\n",
    "ax = study_area.plot(ax=ax, edgecolor='red', facecolor=transparent)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Alternatively, if we have a polygon, we can use ``intersection`` to trim the GeoDataFrame\n",
    "geometry to only the overlapping areas."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "taz_jupiter_irregular.geometry = taz_jupiter_irregular.intersection(irregular_polygon)"
   ]
  },
  {

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "An important feature to consider if using this method is that the operation\n",
    "does not actually change the set of rows or any other data included in the \n",
    "GeoDataFrame.  If, for example, we apply it to the set of TAZ's from the square\n",
    "clipped region, we can get a map that looks identical, but the GeoDataFrame will\n",
    "still retain all the data rows from the previous version, just with some geometry\n",
    "values set as empty."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",

       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"

    }

   "source": [

    "transparent = (0,0,0,0)\n",
    "lines = ax.plot(*irregular_polygon.exterior.xy, color='r')"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "toc-hr-collapsed": false
   },
   "source": [
    "## Joining by Geography"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A common task in geographic analysis is joining two sets of geographic data \n",
    "together.  We actually did a simple version of this just above, when we joined\n",
    "the TAZ data with the study area, although the study area had only a single polygon\n",
    "and no other associated data, so the results are not particularly inspiring.\n",
    "\n",
    "As a more sophisticated example, let's consider the micro-area zone (MAZ) system from \n",
    "SERPM8.  The MAZ are smaller zones nested inside TAZ's, used to provide a higher resolution of data, \n",
    "particularly for transit travel. Using the TAZ system is sometimes too coarse for \n",
    "this purpose, as it may be convenient to walk to a bus stop located on a TAZ boundary\n",
    "only for some parts of the zone, while the walking from the far side of the\n",
    "same TAZ to the bus stop might be unreasonably far.  \n",
    "\n",
    "Like the TAZ system, the MAZ system for SERPM8 is given by a shape file, and is included\n",
    "in the tutorial data, so we can load it in the same way."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 33,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "mazshape_filename = tt.data('SERPM8-MAZSHAPE')\n",
    "maz = gpd.read_file(mazshape_filename)"
   ]
  },
  {

     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "len(maz_jupiter)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To create a joined GeoDataFrame, we can use the same [``overlay``](http://geopandas.org/reference/geopandas.overlay.html) function we used to clip\n",
    "the TAZ's, although we will intersect the TAZ and MAZ geometries."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "maz_taz = gpd.overlay(maz_jupiter, taz_jupiter, how='intersection')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The joined GeoDataFrame has all the columns from both the MAZ and TAZ source data.  In cases\n",

    "columns are retained, and they are labeled with \"\\_1\" and \"\\_2\" suffixes."
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Because we know that the MAZ's are supposed to be nested within the TAZ's, we\n",
    "would normally expect that the joined data would have exactly one row for each of the\n",
    "361 MAZ's, and that some TAZ's would be duplicated.  However, that's not what has happened."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 41,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "437"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 41,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "len(maz_taz)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "toc-hr-collapsed": true
   },
   "source": [
    "### Managing Errors in Joining Spatial Data\n",
    "\n",
    "The joined data has 564 new zones, 203 more than we expected.  There are two\n",
    "reasons for this discrepancy, although both are a result of the two zone systems\n",
    "being misaligned.\n",
    "\n",
    "The first reason is related to the limits computer precision: some of the new \n",
    "zones are merely slivers of space that arise due to rounding errors on the\n",
    "computer placement of vertices.  If we evaluate the area of the first 5 zones\n",
    "in the joined data table, we see that one of the zones is only 1.878×10<sup>-3</sup> \n",
    "square feet, or about a quarter of a square inch.\n",
    "Clearly, this isn't a real zone!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 42,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "0    4.442490e+06\n",
       "1    1.405994e+07\n",
       "2    3.336191e+06\n",
       "3    3.096111e+07\n",
       "4    2.778533e+07\n",
       "dtype: float64"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 42,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "maz_taz.head().area"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The seconds reason that extra zones are found in this join is because the two\n",
    "zone systems are not always carefully aligned by the analysts who originally drew \n",
    "the zones, particularly in areas that are not functionally important. \n",
    "For example, here are the boundaries for the TAZ and MAZ systems, superimposed over \n",
    "a map of the The Loxahatchee Club golf course in Jupiter.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 43,
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 720x720 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = tt.mapping.make_basemap(xlim=(938500,945500), ylim=(937500,944500), zoom=15, \n",
    "                             tiles=tt.mapping.providers.OpenStreetMap.Mapnik.url, epsg=2236, axis='off')\n",
    "ax = taz_jupiter.plot(ax=ax, edgecolor='blue', linewidth=2, facecolor=transparent )\n",
    "ax = maz_jupiter.plot(ax=ax, edgecolor='red', linewidth=1, facecolor=transparent )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "When the intersection of the two zone systems is computed, half a dozen extraneous small zones \n",
    "are generated along the lake that forms the western edge of the golf course, but these are not\n",
    "actually meaningful activity locations and are not relevant for transortation analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "The possible solutions to both problems are the same, given that we know that the \"correct\" join solution\n",
    "will have exactly one zone in the result for each MAZ."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "toc-hr-collapsed": false
   },
   "source": [
    "#### Dropping Extra Pieces"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "toc-hr-collapsed": false
   },
   "source": [
    "One possible solution is to take the joined data we already have, and remove all \n",
    "the extra pieces of zones that were created, retaining only the largest main \n",
    "section of each MAZ.\n",
    "To do this, we can sort zones in the joined GeoDataFrame by area, \n",
    "and retain only the largest zone from each group of duplicated MAZ codes.\n",
    "\n",
    "First, we'll use the argsort method, to get the order of the joined zones, if ordered\n",
    "by area.  Then we feed that into the ``iloc`` indexer to actually sort the rows as\n",
    "indicated.  The argsort returns values in ascending order by default, so all the small\n",
    "slivers and bits of zones we want to discard will appear first."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 44,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "maz_taz = maz_taz.iloc[maz_taz.area.argsort()] "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then, we can drop duplicate MAZ values from the table, keeping only the last instance\n",
    "of each MAZ, which is the one we want.  In theory, if the two zones systems are very poorly\n",
    "aligned, this process could drop the wrong part of the zones, although in almost all \n",
    "cases it will work fine."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 45,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "maz_taz = maz_taz.drop_duplicates('MAZ', keep='last')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 46,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "361"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 46,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "len(maz_taz)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "One drawback of this method is that some small gaps may be left in the resulting\n",
    "joined GeoDataFrame zones, in the spaces that are removed, as illustrated below.  \n",
    "This may or may not be problematic, depending on the application."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 47,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 720x720 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = tt.mapping.make_basemap(xlim=(938500,945500), ylim=(937500,944500), zoom=15, \n",
    "                             tiles=tt.mapping.providers.OpenStreetMap.Mapnik.url, epsg=2236, axis='off')\n",
    "ax = maz_taz.plot(ax=ax, edgecolor='k', linewidth=2, facecolor='r', alpha=0.5 )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Joining on Centroids\n",
    "\n",
    "An alternate solution is to join the TAZ and MAZ data in a entirely different manner.\n",
    "Rather than joining the two GeoDataFrames based on the area polygons in each, we\n",
    "can join based on the area polygons for TAZ's and centroids for MAZ's.\n",
    "To do this, we'll use the [sjoin](http://geopandas.org/reference/geopandas.sjoin.html)\n",
    "method.\n",
    "\n",
    "First, we'll need a version of the MAZ GeoDataFrame that has only centroid points\n",
    "in the `geometry` column, instead of polygons.  To create this, start by making a copy of the\n",
    "original data (assuming we want to save it for later)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 48,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "maz_points = maz_jupiter.copy()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then we want to change the geometry to be points instead of polygons.\n",
    "(Both [Point](https://shapely.readthedocs.io/en/stable/manual.html#points) \n",
    "and [Polygon](https://shapely.readthedocs.io/en/stable/manual.html#polygons) \n",
    "are specific object types in the shapely package that is used by GeoPandas.)\n",
    "We could simply use the 'centroid' attribute of the geometry column to find new centroid \n",
    "for each zone, but in this data we already have X and Y values for a centroid,\n",
    "so we'll prefer to use those.  We can uses the [apply](https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.apply.html) method of DataFrames \n",
    "to create Point values, and assign those values into the geometry column."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 49,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from shapely.geometry import Point\n",
    "maz_points.geometry = maz_points.apply(lambda x: Point(x.POINT_X, x.POINT_Y), axis=1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we are ready to conduct a spatial join using the\n",
    "[sjoin](http://geopandas.org/reference/geopandas.sjoin.html) function.\n",
    "Like the overlay function, this function accepts two GeoDataFrames and returns\n",
    "one, with general data columns from both inputs.  \n",
    "Unlike the overlay function, the [sjoin](http://geopandas.org/reference/geopandas.sjoin.html) does not create any new geometries; \n",
    "instead, the resulting GeoDataFrame contains geometry from either\n",
    "the left (first argument) or right (second argument) input GeoDataFrames."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 50,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sjoined = gpd.sjoin(maz_points, taz_jupiter, how='left', op='within')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 51,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "361"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 51,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "len(sjoined)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 52,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [
       "<div>\n",
       "<style scoped>\n",
       "    .dataframe tbody tr th:only-of-type {\n",
       "        vertical-align: middle;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "\n",
       "    .dataframe tbody tr th {\n",
       "        vertical-align: top;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "\n",
       "    .dataframe thead th {\n",
       "        text-align: right;\n",
       "    }\n",
       "</style>\n",
       "<table border=\"1\" class=\"dataframe\">\n",
       "  <thead>\n",
       "    <tr style=\"text-align: right;\">\n",
       "      <th></th>\n",
       "      <th>OBJECTID_left</th>\n",
       "      <th>MAZ</th>\n",
       "      <th>SHAPE_LENG</th>\n",
       "      <th>SHAPE_AREA</th>\n",
       "      <th>ACRES</th>\n",
       "      <th>POINT_X</th>\n",
       "      <th>POINT_Y</th>\n",
       "      <th>geometry</th>\n",
       "      <th>index_right</th>\n",
       "      <th>OBJECTID_right</th>\n",
       "      <th>...</th>\n",
       "      <th>COUNTY</th>\n",
       "      <th>CENSUSTAZ</th>\n",
       "      <th>TAZ_BF</th>\n",
       "      <th>FIX</th>\n",
       "      <th>AREA</th>\n",

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Creating a Crosswalk Dictionary from the Joined Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We will sometimes be given a MAZ id but want to get the TAZ id instead.  As this is\n",
    "a one-to-many mapping (every MAZ is in one and only one TAZ, but each TAZ can contain\n",
    "multiple MAZ's), it is convenient to express this mapping as a Python dictionary.\n",
    "This can be done easily if the ``index`` of the GeoDataFrame is set to be the MAZ."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 57,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sjoined.index=sjoined.MAZ"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 58,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "maz_taz_crosswalk = dict(sjoined.TAZ_MPO)"
   ]
  },
